  "reasoning": "First, minimize f(x,y)=x^4+y^4-x^2y-xy^2 subject to x>0, y>0, x+y≤1. Let s=x+y, p=xy. Then f=s^4-4s^2p+2p^2-sp. For fixed s, f is quadratic in p with positive coefficient, so the minimum over p occurs at the boundary p=s^2/4 (maximum p). Substituting gives f(s)=s^4/8-s^3/4=s^3(s-2)/8, which is decreasing for s∈(0,1]. Thus the minimum is at s=1, yielding f=-1/8. Then k = -1/8 + 401/8 = 400/8 = 50.

Next, compute the probability that gcd(n^n+50, n+1)=1 for n chosen uniformly from {1,…,2023!}. Note that if p divides n+1, then n≡-1 mod p, so n^n+50≡(-1)^n+50 mod p. Thus p divides n^n+50 iff (-1)^n+50≡0 mod p. For even n, this requires p|51 (p=3 or 17); for odd n, p|49 (p=7). Hence gcd>1 iff (n even and 3|n+1 or 17|n+1) or (n odd and 7|n+1).

Since 2023! is divisible by 2,3,7,17, the distribution of n modulo 714=lcm(2,3,7,17) is uniform. Count residues r (0≤r≤713) satisfying the condition for gcd=1. Failures: even r with r+1 divisible by 3: 119; divisible by 17: 21; overlap: 7 → even failures=133. Odd r with r+1 divisible by 7: 51. Total failures=184, so successes=530. Probability=530/714=265/357.",
